Explanation:

We use two queues, queue1 and queue2, to implement a LIFO stack. The push operation appends the element to queue1 and queue2. The pop operation checks if queue2 is empty. If it is, it means the stack is empty, so it returns -1. Otherwise, it pops an element from queue2 and returns it. The top function returns the last element from queue1, which represents the top of the stack. The empty function checks if both queues are empty, returning True if so, otherwise False.

This solution has a time complexity of O(1) for pop and top operations, as they both operate on the current front elements of the queues. The space complexity is O(2n), where n is the number of elements in the stack, as we use two queues to store the stack elements. The energy implications are low, as the operations are efficient and do not consume significant energy.

